## Error Handling Requirements

**Every user-facing operation must handle failure states** unless explicitly building a prototype.

```typescript
// ❌ Wrong: No error handling
async function saveUser(user: User) {
  await fetch('/api/users', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: JSON.stringify(user)
  });
}

// ✅ Correct: Handle errors explicitly
async function saveUser(user: User): Promise<Result> {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('/api/users', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify(user)
    });
    
    if (!response.ok) {
      return { success: false, error: 'Failed to save user' };
    }
    
    return { success: true };
  } catch (error) {
    return { success: false, error: 'Network error' };
  }
}
```

**Use type-safe error handling patterns when available** (Result types, Either, etc.).

---

## Verification Checklist

Before considering any change complete:

- [ ] Only modified files required for the task
- [ ] No unrelated formatting or refactoring changes
- [ ] Existing behavior preserved (no visual or functional changes)
- [ ] No new dependencies added
- [ ] No new architectural patterns introduced
- [ ] Followed local directory conventions
- [ ] Added comments only for non-obvious decisions
- [ ] Error cases handled appropriately
- [ ] Code compiles without new TypeScript errors
- [ ] No unused imports or variables introduced

**If you cannot verify all items, explain what's unclear and ask for guidance.**
